				\begin{document}$$\lambda _1+\lambda _2+\dots +\lambda _r = n$$\end{document}λ1+λ2+⋯+λr=n. Partitions wherein the parts are distinct have long played a key role in the theory of partitions, dating back to Euler’s discovery and proof that the number of partitions of weight n into distinct parts equals the number of partitions of weight n into odd parts.

A clear refinement along these lines is to require distinct parts based on parity; i.e., to require either all of the even parts to be distinct or all of the odd parts to be distinct (while allowing the frequency of the other parts to be unrestricted). This leads to two types of partitions, those known as PED partitions (wherein the even parts must be distinct and the odd parts are unrestricted) and POD partitions (wherein the odd parts must be distinct and the even parts are unrestricted). We then define two corresponding enumerating functions, \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
